The paper deals with distributed algorithms for solving network design problems, which are typically studied in the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The use of convex programming and approximation algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Computational Geometry (cs.CG) sub-categories. Finally, the mention of matching centralized approximation algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category, which often deals with optimization problems.
